@Jim 
How can I be any clearer than I was?  "Left/right/up/down is SO much more self-evident and useful."  It is learned much earlier and thus is more natural than compass directions acquired later in life.   Worse, compass directions are of course relative to where one is standing and looking, as opposed to static portions of a held page.

The top of the page is the top, not the "north".  The left side of the page is the left, not the "west".  How is this objection hard to understand?  You are free to disagree, but my modest position is not difficult to parse.

@B 

Some people always think their inferior way is the best. Solvers use it as shorthand. NW is much easier to type than upper left, and if you shorten that, you'll get UL, which no one outside of the group will know, unlike the compass points. 

I think you think it's some kind of elitist or fancy nomenclature, but it's really not. Everyone knows the directions - it's the opposite of elitist.

